goals.question: What is the distribution of obesity rates across all states?
goals.visualization: choropleth map of obesity rates by state
goals.rationale: This visualization will allow us to see which states have the highest and lowest obesity rates, and identify any regional patterns.

goals.question: Is there a correlation between state population and obesity rates?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of state population vs. obesity rates
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a relationship between state population and obesity rates, which could inform public health policies and interventions.

goals.question: What is the distribution of obesity rates by gender?
goals.visualization: stacked bar chart of obesity rates by gender
goals.rationale: This visualization will allow us to see if there are any significant differences in obesity rates between genders, which could inform targeted interventions.

goals.question: What is the trend in obesity rates over time?
goals.visualization: line chart of obesity rates over time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if obesity rates are increasing, decreasing, or staying the same over time, which could inform public health policies and interventions.

goals.question: What is the distribution of obesity rates by income level?
goals.visualization: box plot of obesity rates by income level
goals.rationale: This visualization will allow us to see if there are any significant differences in obesity rates between income levels, which could inform targeted interventions and policies to address health disparities.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Read the US states shapefile
    us_states = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PublicaMundi/MappingAPI/master/data/geojson/us-states.json")

    # Merge the obesity data with the shapefile
    merged_data = us_states.set_index("id").join(data.set_index("id"))

    # Create the choropleth map
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(15, 10))
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.1)
    merged_data.plot(column="rate", cmap="coolwarm", linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor="0.8", legend=True, cax=cax)

    # Set the title
    plt.title("What is the distribution of obesity rates across all states?", wrap=True)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['state'], data['rate'])
    ax.set_xlabel('State')
    ax.set_ylabel('Obesity Rate')
    ax.set_title('Is there a correlation between state population and obesity rates?')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="States")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Assuming the dataset contains a 'gender' column
    gender_data = data.groupby(['state', 'gender'])['rate'].sum().unstack()
    ax = gender_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of obesity rates by gender?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Gender')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['id'] = pd.to_datetime(data['id'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['id'])]
    
    plt.plot(data['id'], data['rate'])
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.title('What is the trend in obesity rates over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(['Obesity Rate'])
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data.boxplot(column='rate', by='state', grid=False, vert=False, figsize=(10, 8))
    plt.title('What is the distribution of obesity rates by income level?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Obesity Rate')
    plt.ylabel('State')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Income Level', loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
